1: What kind of bugs did you find?
1.1: fifo1.vhd

Scoreboard tells us:
Data output is not the oldest data in FIFO, full signal is not same for DUT and model, one place signal is not same for DUT and model, one data signal is not same for DUT and model, empty signal is not same for DUT and model and one data signal is not same for DUT and model.

This means in fifo1.vhd data will be written into the memory even though it should be full according to the specified depth_g = 5.

1.2: fifo2.vhd

Scoreboard tells us:
Data output is not the oldest data in FIFO. 

This happens very often when constraining data_to_DUT to numbers close to the largest number 32-bit integer can hold. If the constraint is made so that MSB is not included (like it was in the beginning and I was wondering why no bugs seem to be present) then the scoreboard does not give any errors as if the code would be working fine even though it is not fine. So in fifo2.vhd MSB is always written to 0 even though it should sometimes be 1.   

2: (Optional) To implement the same kind of behaviour in fifo.vhd, which code lines should you edit and how?
(Give line number and your modification)
1.1: fifo1.vhd

Remove this check on line 116: if full_r = '0' then so write to FIFO without checking if it is full or not.

1.2: fifo2.vhd

Edit line 125: fifo_buffer_r (in_ptr_r) <= data_in; to fifo_buffer_r (in_ptr_r) <= '0' & data_in(data_width_g-2 downto 0); so write 0 to MSB always instead of correct behavior and keep rest of the bits correct. 

3: Did you have to modify your environment to see the bugs? Where and why?

Not needed as we made the environment comprehensive enough from the beginning.

4: Did you have to modify your tests or sequences to see the bugs? Where and why?

For fifo1.vhd test_base found the bug right away but random_test did not. We changed the constraints for distributions of write_enable and read_enable so that writes would be more likely to happen and reads less likely to happen. This change made the random_test notice the bug too.

For fifo2.vhd neither of the two tests would catch the error at first. However, the random test caught the error after first removing the data_to_DUT value range constraint so constraint c_data {data_to_DUT >= 0; data_to_DUT < 1024; }. Then the error could be pointed directly to higher data values and ultimately to the MSB when writing. Also, we changed the test_base to directly write the largest possible value a 32-bit number could hold and then read it to confirm this wrong behavior.
